162. Paniceis. What town, if any, supplied this pun is unknown. Schoell suggests that the word may be Poenicis with ei the old spelling of classica] i (see note on the Argument), and punctuates Opus Panic-is, est opus &a Placentinis puns on (l) placenta, ‘a cake,' (2) Placentia, the town in N. Italy.

163. Turdetanis. This Spanish tribe in S. Spain had perhaps been brought into notice through the military operations during the Second Punic War. The name is of course selected for the sake of a pun on turdus. Picedulensibus. No satisfactory guess has been made about the locality of this tribe or parish, whose name suggests the ficedula, ⁴ beccafico.' Spengel (Philoloyus xxxvii. 425) proposes Fidemlensibus, since a town Fideculae is mentioned in Valer. MaX. vii. 6, and suggests that fidcculae, ‘lyre-strings³ may have been the name of some kind of pastry.
